  <h1>What to Do After Retaliatory Firing</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Riley Chen (RC), Employment &amp; Civil Rights Practice Lead. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>1. Act immediately — deadlines are short</h2><p>OSHA retaliation: 30 days. Title VII, ADA, ADEA retaliation: 180/300 days to file EEOC charge. FLSA retaliation: 2 years to file directly in court. The OSHA deadline is the most critical — 30 days from termination is extremely short. If OSHA applies, contact an attorney today.</p>
  <h2>2. Document the connection</h2><p>Write down the exact sequence: when you engaged in protected activity, every communication about it, when the adverse action followed, what was said. The timeline connecting the protected activity to the firing is your core evidence.</p>
  <h2>3. Preserve all documents</h2><p>Save all emails, performance reviews, termination letter, and internal communications to personal storage before returning company equipment. Courts can sanction employers for destroying evidence — but you can&rsquo;t control what they destroy once you&rsquo;re gone.</p>
  <h2>4. Consult an employment attorney</h2><p>Most employment attorneys take retaliation cases on contingency (no fee unless you win) because attorney fees are recoverable under most anti-retaliation statutes. Contact one before the EEOC deadline — their help structuring the charge is valuable.</p>
